With increasing urbanization, weâre losing our night skies. Year after year, pure dark skies are vanishing at an alarming rate.

The shrill sound of the alarm cut through the stillness of the early morning, jarring me out of a deep sleep. My eyes fluttered open, disoriented and groggy, as the relentless beeping persisted, demanding my attention. I fumbled to silence it, my hand reaching blindly for the snooze button as I tried to shake off the drowsiness that clung to me. The room was still dark, and the comfort of my bed seemed to mock me as I reluctantly dragged myself out of its warmth. Each morning, the alarm felt like an unwelcome intrusion into the peace of sleep, a reminder that the day had begun whether I was ready or not.

As I sat up, the reality of the day ahead slowly crept in, but the immediate discomfort of waking up was always the hardest part. The alarmâs sound, which once seemed like an innocent signal to begin the day, had now become synonymous with the rush of obligations and responsibilities. Still, there was no escaping it. The alarm had done its job, pulling me from the haze of sleep and into the demands of the waking world. Though I longed to drift back to sleep for just a few more minutes, I knew that the rhythm of the day was already underway, and I had no choice but to follow its pace.
